1. Types of Interfaces

Java mainly provides two types of interfaces.

Functional Interface
Contains only one abstract method.
May contain any number of default methods.
May contain any number of static methods.
Introduced mainly for Lambda Expressions.

Examples

Runnable
ActionListener
ItemListener

Example

interface Demo
{
    void display();
}

Only one abstract method is present.

Marker Interface

A Marker Interface is an interface that does not contain any methods or fields.

It is simply used to provide special information to the JVM.

Examples

Serializable
Cloneable

Example

interface Student
{

}
2. Implementing an Interface

To implement an interface, we use the implements keyword.

Syntax

class ClassName implements InterfaceName
{

}

Example

interface Animal
{
    void sound();
}

class Dog implements Animal
{
    public void sound()
    {
        System.out.println("Barking");
    }
}
3. Multiple Interfaces

A Java class can implement multiple interfaces.

Syntax

class Demo implements Interface1, Interface2
{

}

The class must override all abstract methods from every interface.

Example

interface A
{
    void show();
}

interface B
{
    void display();
}

class Test implements A,B
{

}
4. Abstract Class vs Interface
Abstract Class	Interface
Used when classes have an "is-a" relationship	Used by unrelated classes
Only one abstract class can be extended	Multiple interfaces can be implemented
Can contain abstract and normal methods	Contains abstract, default and static methods
Used to share common implementation	Used to provide common functionality
5. Real-Time Applications of Interface

Interfaces are widely used in software development.

Examples

Banking

A Credit Card interface can have different implementations.

Rupees
Dollars
Pounds

Each bank provides its own implementation.

API Development

Interfaces expose project APIs to other projects.

Example

HDFC Bank can expose services to shopping applications.

Software Design

Interfaces help developers write flexible and reusable code.

Full Abstraction

Interfaces achieve complete abstraction.

6. Wrapper Classes

Wrapper Classes convert primitive data types into objects.

Primitive data types cannot directly behave as objects.

Wrapper classes solve this problem.

Definition

A Wrapper Class wraps a primitive data type inside an object.

Primitive Data Types and Wrapper Classes
Primitive	Wrapper Class
byte	Byte
short	Short
int	Integer
long	Long
float	Float
double	Double
char	Character
boolean	Boolean
7. Why Wrapper Classes?

Wrapper Classes are required because

Collections store only objects.
Generic classes work only with objects.
Java utility classes use objects.
Primitive values must sometimes be converted into objects.
Wrapper classes provide conversion methods.
8. Wrapping

Converting a primitive value into an object.

Example

int x = 25;

Integer obj = Integer.valueOf(x);

(Older constructor syntax like new Integer(x) appears in the slides but is deprecated in modern Java.)

9. Unwrapping

Converting an object back into a primitive.

Example

Integer obj = Integer.valueOf(25);

int number = obj.intValue();
10. Real World Example

Suppose Amazon collects customer information.

Name
Phone Number
Debit Card Number
Address

String values are already objects.

But

Debit Card Number
Phone Number

may be primitive values.

Before sending data to the server, Java converts primitive values into objects using Wrapper Classes.

